    <abstract>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">ProActive</emphasis> is a <emphasis
      role="bold">GRID</emphasis> Java library for <emphasis
      role="bold">parallel</emphasis>, <emphasis
      role="bold">distributed</emphasis>, and <emphasis
      role="bold">concurrent</emphasis> computing, also featuring <emphasis
      role="bold">mobility</emphasis> and <emphasis
      role="bold">security</emphasis> in a uniform framework. With a reduced
      set of simple primitives, <emphasis role="bold">ProActive</emphasis>
      provides a comprehensive API allowing to simplify the programming of
      applications that are distributed on <emphasis role="bold">Local Area
      Network</emphasis> (LAN), on <emphasis role="bold">cluster of
      workstations</emphasis>, on <emphasis role="bold">P2P desktop
      Grids</emphasis>, or on I<emphasis role="bold">nternet Grids</emphasis>.
      The library is based on an Active Object pattern that is a uniform way
      to encapsulate:</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>a <emphasis role="bold">remotely accessible
            object</emphasis>,</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a <emphasis role="bold">thread</emphasis> as an asynchronous
            activity,</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>an <emphasis role="bold">actor</emphasis> with its own
            script,</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a <emphasis role="bold">server</emphasis> of incoming
            requests,</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a <emphasis role="bold">mobile</emphasis> and potentially
            secure entity.</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <para>On top of those basic features, ProActive also includes <emphasis
      role="bold">advanced</emphasis> aspects, such as:</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>Typed <emphasis role="bold">Group</emphasis>
            Communications</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><emphasis role="bold">OO SPMD</emphasis></para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>Distributed and Hierarchical <emphasis
            role="bold">Components</emphasis></para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><emphasis role="bold">Security</emphasis></para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><emphasis role="bold">Fault Tolerance</emphasis> with
            checkpointing</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a <emphasis role="bold">P2P</emphasis> infrastructure</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a Graphical User Interface <emphasis
            role="bold">IC2D</emphasis></para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>a powerful <emphasis role="bold">deployment</emphasis> model
            based on XML descriptors</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para><emphasis role="bold">File transfer</emphasis> capabilities
            over the <emphasis role="bold">Grid</emphasis></para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <para><emphasis role="bold">ProActive</emphasis> is only made of
      standard Java classes, and requires <emphasis role="bold">no changes to
      the Java Virtual Machine</emphasis>, no preprocessing or compiler
      modification; programmers write standard Java code. Based on a simple
      Meta-Object Protocol, the library is itself extensible, making the
      system open for adaptations and optimizations. <emphasis
      role="bold">ProActive</emphasis> currently uses the <emphasis
      role="bold">RMI</emphasis> Java standard library as default portable
      transport layer.</para>

      <para><emphasis role="bold">ProActive</emphasis> features several
      optimizations improving performance. For instance, whenever two active
      objects are located within the same virtual machine, a direct
      communication is always achieved, without going through the network
      stack. This optimization is ensured even when the co-location occurs
      after a migration of one or both of the active objects.</para>

      <para><emphasis role="bold">ProActive</emphasis> and the (de facto)
      <emphasis role="bold">Standards</emphasis>: ProActive has an
      architecture that allows the library to <emphasis
      role="bold">interoperate</emphasis> with various official or de facto
      <emphasis role="bold">standards</emphasis>:</para>

      <para><itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>Web Service Exportation</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>HTTP Transport, RMI/SSH tunneling Transport</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>ssh, scp, rsh, rcp</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>Globus GT2, GT3 and GT4, Unicore, GLite, ARC (NorduGrid),
            GSI-SSH</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>LSF, PBS, Sun Grid Engine, OAR</para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist></para>

      <para>Please send us comments, suggestions, bug reports at <ulink
      url="mailto:proactive@objectweb.org">proactive@objectweb.org</ulink>
      Your input will be greatly appreciated.</para>
    </abstract>
